It&#39;s normal behavior for heap usage to rise to near max, then drop 
significantly, as the VM goes through garbage-collection cycles.

It&#39;s our goal for there to be no OOMEs no matter how large or 
long-running a crawl. (The crawl may be slower, as the on-disk data 
structures get larger and more seeks are required for normal URL 
handling, but as long as you have disk space, there should be forward 
progress without memory errors.) And, as of the version you&#39;re using 
(1.14.4), we believe we&#39;ve hit that goal except in some very rare and 
obscure edge cases. So I do suspect your OOMEs may have been due to some 
VM/GC/platform bug fixed since 1.5.0_06.

If it recurs and the crawler manages to pause in reaction to the OOME, 
the &#39;jmap -histo [PID]&#39; output for the VM can often give a hint as to 
what unwanted object retention caused the problem. (Also, the OOME 
errors in later JVMs are sometimes more informative.)

FYI, BroadScope is a very old implementation; we recommend using the 
DecidingScope, with rules adjusted to allow a broad crawl, if possible 
and as preparation for future versions (where BroadScope class goes 
away). But its use isn&#39;t implicated in the OOMEs, and if it&#39;s working 
for you there&#39;s no urgent reason to change.

- Gordon @ IA

